    <p class="paragraph">
        Ruth Bader Ginsburg, born in New York, graduated first in her class at Columbia Law school. Post-graduation, she <br>
        faced difficulty when searching for a job due to discrimination and went to Sweden to join the Columbia Project on <br>
        International Civil Procedures, her other passion. When she returned from Sweden, she became a professor at Rutgers University <br>
        Law School prior to transferring to Columbia University. She led the fight against gender discrimination with the Women’s Rights <br>
        Project of the American Civil Liberties, arguing 6 landmark cases before the Supreme Court. She served on the U.S. Court of <br>
        Appeals per Jimmy Carter’s request prior to being appointed to Supreme Court by Bill Clinton in 1993. There, she continued to <br>
        fight for women’s rights while serving as justice. She is still is one of the most avid questioners on the bench today.
    </p>
